#: ../../../intro/tutorial.rst:65
msgid "Defining our Item"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/tutorial.rst:67
msgid ""
"`Items` are containers that will be loaded with the scraped data; they work "
"like simple python dicts but provide additional protection against "
"populating undeclared fields, to prevent typos."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/tutorial.rst:71
msgid ""
"They are declared by creating a :class:`scrapy.Item <scrapy.item.Item>` "
"class and defining its attributes as :class:`scrapy.Field <scrapy.item."
"Field>` objects, like you will in an ORM (don't worry if you're not familiar "
"with ORMs, you will see that this is an easy task)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/tutorial.rst:76
msgid ""
"We begin by modeling the item that we will use to hold the sites data "
"obtained from dmoz.org, as we want to capture the name, url and description "
"of the sites, we define fields for each of these three attributes. To do "
"that, we edit ``items.py``, found in the ``tutorial`` directory. Our Item "
"class looks like this::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/tutorial.rst:81
msgid ""
"import scrapy\n"
"\n"
"class DmozItem(scrapy.Item):\n"
"    title = scrapy.Field()\n"
"    link = scrapy.Field()\n"
"    desc = scrapy.Field()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/tutorial.rst:88
msgid ""
"This may seem complicated at first, but defining the item allows you to use "
"other handy components of Scrapy that need to know how your item looks."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/tutorial.rst:92
msgid "Our first Spider"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/tutorial.rst:94
msgid ""
"Spiders are user-written classes used to scrape information from a domain "
"(or group of domains)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/tutorial.rst:97
msgid ""
"They define an initial list of URLs to download, how to follow links, and "
"how to parse the contents of those pages to extract :ref:`items <topics-"
"items>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/tutorial.rst:100
msgid ""
"To create a Spider, you must subclass :class:`scrapy.Spider <scrapy.spider."
"Spider>` and define the three main mandatory attributes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/tutorial.rst:103
msgid ""
":attr:`~scrapy.spider.Spider.name`: identifies the Spider. It must be "
"unique, that is, you can't set the same name for different Spiders."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/tutorial.rst:106
msgid ""
":attr:`~scrapy.spider.Spider.start_urls`: is a list of URLs where the Spider "
"will begin to crawl from.  So, the first pages downloaded will be those "
"listed here. The subsequent URLs will be generated successively from data "
"contained in the start URLs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/tutorial.rst:111
msgid ""
":meth:`~scrapy.spider.Spider.parse` is a method of the spider, which will be "
"called with the downloaded :class:`~scrapy.http.Response` object of each "
"start URL. The response is passed to the method as the first and only "
"argument."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/tutorial.rst:116
msgid ""
"This method is responsible for parsing the response data and extracting "
"scraped data (as scraped items) and more URLs to follow."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/tutorial.rst:119
msgid ""
"The :meth:`~scrapy.spider.Spider.parse` method is in charge of processing "
"the response and returning scraped data (as :class:`~scrapy.item.Item` "
"objects) and more URLs to follow (as :class:`~scrapy.http.Request` objects)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/tutorial.rst:123
msgid ""
"This is the code for our first Spider; save it in a file named ``dmoz_spider."
"py`` under the ``tutorial/spiders`` directory::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/tutorial.rst:126
msgid ""
"import scrapy\n"
"\n"
"class DmozSpider(scrapy.Spider):\n"
"    name = \"dmoz\"\n"
"    allowed_domains = [\"dmoz.org\"]\n"
"    start_urls = [\n"
"        \"http://www.dmoz.org/Computers/Programming/Languages/Python/Books/"
"\",\n"
"        \"http://www.dmoz.org/Computers/Programming/Languages/Python/"
"Resources/\"\n"
"    ]\n"
"\n"
"    def parse(self, response):\n"
"        filename = response.url.split(\"/\")[-2]\n"
"        with open(filename, 'wb') as f:\n"
"            f.write(response.body)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/tutorial.rst:142
msgid "Crawling"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/tutorial.rst:144
msgid ""
"To put our spider to work, go to the project's top level directory and run::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/tutorial.rst:146 ../../../intro/tutorial.rst:371
msgid "scrapy crawl dmoz"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/tutorial.rst:148
msgid ""
"The ``crawl dmoz`` command runs the spider for the ``dmoz.org`` domain. You "
"will get an output similar to this::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/tutorial.rst:151
msgid ""
"2014-01-23 18:13:07-0400 [scrapy] INFO: Scrapy started (bot: tutorial)\n"
"2014-01-23 18:13:07-0400 [scrapy] INFO: Optional features available: ...\n"
"2014-01-23 18:13:07-0400 [scrapy] INFO: Overridden settings: {}\n"
"2014-01-23 18:13:07-0400 [scrapy] INFO: Enabled extensions: ...\n"
"2014-01-23 18:13:07-0400 [scrapy] INFO: Enabled downloader middlewares: ...\n"
"2014-01-23 18:13:07-0400 [scrapy] INFO: Enabled spider middlewares: ...\n"
"2014-01-23 18:13:07-0400 [scrapy] INFO: Enabled item pipelines: ...\n"
